description:
What: In lichen_l2_enable() disable path, if k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_MSEC(100)) times out, the code calls k_mutex_init(&rx_mutex) then k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_FOREVER) on the same mutex. This reinitializes a mutex that may be held by another thread.

Why it matters: POSIX and Zephyr semantics state that reinitializing a held mutex is undefined behavior. If the timeout occurred because another thread holds rx_mutex (e.g., lichen_l2_input in progress), calling k_mutex_init() corrupts the mutex state while that thread is still using it.

The code comment mentions 'possible aborted thread' but the check at line 979 (lichen_lora_l2_needs_reinit()) should have caught true abort scenarios. This timeout path suggests a non-abort deadlock or slow operation, not an aborted thread.

Evidence:
```c
if (k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_MSEC(100)) != 0) {
    LOG_DBG("lichen_l2: rx_mutex timeout, reinitializing (possible aborted thread)");
    k_mutex_init(&rx_mutex);  // UB if mutex is legitimately held
    k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
}
```
